

**  Q2: What was the problem before BlockingQueue? Why it was introduced?

        Before BlockingQueue, we used to share data between threads using ArrayList or LinkedList.
        But there were multiple problems with that approach:

        Problem 1 — Thread Safety:

        1. ArrayList and LinkedList are not thread-safe. 
        2. If two threads do add() and remove() at the same time, we get ConcurrentModificationException or 
           data corruption. 
        3. To fix this, we had to put synchronized blocks everywhere manually.

        Problem 2 — Manual Wait-Notify Logic:

        1. Even after synchronized, producer thread had to manually check — "is list full? then wait."
        2. Consumer had to check — "is list empty? then wait." This required writing while loop with wait() 
           and notify().calls.
        3. This code was very error-prone — missed signals, spurious wakeups,deadlocks were common bugs.  

        Problem 3 — Boilerplate Code:

        1. Every developer was writing the same wait-notify boilerplate again and again for every producer-consumer 
           use case. No standard solution existed. 
        2. So Java introduced BlockingQueue in Java 5 (JDK 1.5) as part of java.util.concurrent package.
        3. It encapsulated all the synchronization, waiting, and notification logic inside the queue itself.

           1.  put()  -> if queue is full, thread automatically blocks until space is available
           2.  take() -> if queue is empty, thread automatically blocks until element is available
           3.  No manual synchronization needed. No wait-notify needed. Clean and safe.


=============================================================================================================================

** Code Example — OLD way (before BlockingQueue) using wait-notify:

   // Shared list between producer and consumer
    List<String> sharedList = new ArrayList<>();
    int MAX_CAPACITY = 5;
    Object lock = new Object();

    // Producer thread — ugly, error-prone code
    Thread producer = new Thread(() -> {
        while (true) {
            synchronized (lock) {
                // Step 1: manually check if list is full
                while (sharedList.size() == MAX_CAPACITY) {
                    try {
                        lock.wait();   // Step 2: manually wait if full
                    } catch (InterruptedException e) { }
                }
                sharedList.add("Order-" + System.currentTimeMillis());
                lock.notify();         // Step 3: manually notify consumer
            }
        }
    });


** // Consumer thread — same ugly pattern
    Thread consumer = new Thread(() -> {
        while (true) {
            synchronized (lock) {
                // Step 1: manually check if list is empty
                while (sharedList.isEmpty()) {
                    try {
                        lock.wait();   // Step 2: manually wait if empty
                    } catch (InterruptedException e) { }
                }
                String item = sharedList.remove(0);
                lock.notify();         // Step 3: manually notify producer
            }
        }
    });   

 ** // Problems with above code:
    // 1. synchronized block mandatory — forget it and data corrupts
    // 2. while loop with wait() mandatory — forget while and spurious wakeup breaks logic
    // 3. notify() mandatory — forget it and other thread hangs forever (deadlock)
    // 4. ~25 lines of boilerplate just for simple put and take

============================================================================================================================

** Code Example — NEW way (with BlockingQueue) — same thing, clean:

    BlockingQueue<String> queue = new ArrayBlockingQueue<>(5);

    // Producer thread — clean, 1 line
    Thread producer = new Thread(() -> {
        while (true) {
            queue.put("Order-" + System.currentTimeMillis());  // blocks if full, no wait/notify needed
        }
    });

    // Consumer thread — clean, 1 line
    Thread consumer = new Thread(() -> {
        while (true) {
            String item = queue.take();  // blocks if empty, no wait/notify needed
        }
    });   


// Consumer thread — clean, 1 line
    Thread consumer = new Thread(() -> {
        while (true) {
            String item = queue.take();  // blocks if empty, no wait/notify needed
        }
    });

// No synchronized, no wait(), no notify(), no while loop
    // Same functionality in 5 lines instead of 25 lines
    // Thread-safe, backpressure built-in, zero boilerplate
         